# gen295 (basic-chat cat.43 "Famiglia"): two structural moves on the kinship
# class family_relation/1 (kb/core/social.p0, loaded in the hermetic base too),
# not a phrasebook of families:
#   (A) a first-person family STATEMENT -> a warm, honest acknowledgment;
#   (B) a question about PARROT0's family -> an honest decline (it is an AI, it has
#       no family) — inventing a sister's name would be a misclaim, worse than a wall.
# Keys on the class + "my"/"i have" (A) vs "your" (B), so it generalizes to any
# relation and predicate; a non-family turn (name/identity) is left untouched.

# (A) the user's own family — acknowledged, never faked-understood.
> I have two brothers and one sister
< Thanks for telling me about your family -- I'll keep that in mind.
> my father works in a bank
< Thanks for telling me about your family -- I'll keep that in mind.
> my aunt lives in Paris
< Thanks for telling me about your family -- I'll keep that in mind.

# (B) parrot0's own "family" — honest decline, names the relation asked about.
> what is your sister's name
< I'm parrot0, an AI, so I don't have a sister -- no family to name.
> do you have any brothers
< I'm parrot0, an AI, so I don't have a brother -- no family to name.

# a possessive with a vowel-initial relation picks the right article ("an uncle").
> what does your uncle do
< I'm parrot0, an AI, so I don't have an uncle -- no family to name.

# gen297: second-person POSSESSION ("do/you have <kin>") is branch B too, not just
# "your" — but a first-person statement that merely mentions "you" stays branch A.
> you have a brother
< I'm parrot0, an AI, so I don't have a brother -- no family to name.
> my brother knows you
< Thanks for telling me about your family -- I'll keep that in mind.

# NOT stolen: identity / name turns have no kinship term, so mod_family declines
# and the real handlers answer.
> what is your name
< I am parrot0.
